{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529181"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:52:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14366"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.47,0.08,0.28,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3746"},{"type":"tags","id":"3747"},{"type":"tags","id":"3754"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fatigue, dizziness, and shortness of breath. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears pale with conjunctival pallor. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination is otherwise unremarkable. Abdominal examination reveals no tenderness or organomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 75 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMean Corpuscular Volume (MCV): 88 fL (80-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMean Corpuscular Haemoglobin Concentration (MCHC): 320 g/L (310-360)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite Cell Count: 9.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet Count: 280 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EReticulocyte Count: 6% (0.5-2.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate Dehydrogenase (LDH): 210 U/L (100-250)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaptoglobin: 2.0 g/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iron deficiency anaemia","Acute blood loss","Aplastic anaemia","Haemolytic anaemia","Pure red cell aplasia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs of anaemia, and her laboratory results confirm a significant anaemia with a haemoglobin of 75 g/L. The key to differentiating between the various causes of anaemia lies in interpreting the additional laboratory findings. In particular, the reticulocyte count (immature erythrocytes) is helpful for differentiating the causes as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eincreased: blood loss, increased destruction (e.g., haemolytic anaemia). Can be distinguished by clinical history and haemolytic screen, as discussed below.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Edecreased or normal: decreased production (e.g., b12/folate/iron deficiency, pure red cell aplasia, aplastic anaemia)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute blood loss\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. In acute blood loss, the MCV is often normal. The reticulocyte count is mildly elevated, indicating that the bone marrow has just begun to respond to the anaemia. Importantly, the haptoglobin and LDH levels are within normal ranges, which helps to rule out haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E may be normocytic. However, macrocytosis may also be seen due to reticulocytosis as the bone marrow responds to increased red cell destruction, a low haptoglobin (as it binds to free haemoglobin), and an elevated LDH (due to red cell breakdown). None of these features are present in this case. Blood film examination is also helpful to look for:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Espherocytes, agglutination: present in autoimmune haemolytic anaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebite/Pincer cells: present in oxidative haemolysis (e.g., Glucose-6-phoshate dehydrogenase deficiency)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eschistocytes: present in microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia (e.g., thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would present with pancytopenia, affecting all cell lines. In this case, the white cell and platelet counts are normal, ruling out this diagnosis. In aplastic anaemia, there is reticulocytopenia reflecting poor production of erythrocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, which may be caused by chronic blood loss, inadequate uptake or absorption typically presents with a low MCV (microcytic anaemia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure red cell aplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a severe normocytic anaemia with very low reticulocyte count, typically less than 1%. The white cell and platelet counts are usually normal. In this case, the reticulocyte count is elevated, which is inconsistent with pure red cell aplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the acute onset of symptoms, normal red cell indices, and the absence of signs of haemolysis, acute blood loss is the most likely diagnosis. The next steps in management would include identifying and addressing the source of bleeding, which could be occult gastrointestinal bleeding, heavy menstrual bleeding, or other causes of acute blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute blood loss typically presents with normal MCV","Haptoglobin levels are decreased in haemolytic anaemia but normal or elevated in acute blood loss (as an acute phase reactant)","LDH is elevated in haemolytic anaemia but typically normal in acute blood loss."],"references":["Buttarello M. Laboratory diagnosis of anemia: are the old and new red cell parameters useful in classification and treatment, how?. Int J Lab Hematol. 2016;38 Suppl 1:123-132. doi:10.1111/ijlh.12500"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T21:34:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T21:37:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79799"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app